# Localization (UI copy)

Picko is built in Korea but **targets global users**. All **product-facing text** uses **English** as the default language.

## Audience (word choice & tone)

| Layer | Who |
|-------|-----|
| **Core** | **20s–30s** traveling in **Korea** — trend-led discovery, spots worth visiting |
| **Range** | **Teens–40s** — same voice; stay approachable, not childish or corporate |
| **Mindset** | **잘파 (well-informed / trend-conscious)** — wants what’s hot and real; skims fast on mobile |

Write like a **travel + K-culture companion**, not admin software: short, confident, friendly **you**, discovery words (**pick**, **spot**, **trending**, **near you**). Light emoji OK where the prototype uses them (e.g. 🔥). Avoid stiff formality and heavy slang.

Full voice guide: `docs/LANGUAGE.md` · [language-reference.md](../skills/picko-design-system/language-reference.md)

## Must be English

- Button, link, heading, body, empty states, errors, toasts, placeholders
- `aria-label`, `title`, alt text meant for users
- OAuth / auth button labels (`lib/auth/social-providers.ts` `label` fields)
- `app/layout.tsx` document language: `lang="en"`

## Not required to translate (unless asked)

- Code comments, JSDoc, commit messages
- Internal docs (`docs/*.md`) — may stay Korean for the team; still describe UI strings as English when documenting screens
- Mock data place names in Korea (e.g. spot names) — real content, not chrome copy

## Tone (quick)

- Short, scannable; one idea per line where possible
- Sentence case on buttons: `Continue with Google`, `Sign out`
- Prefer **pick / spot / trending** over generic SaaS terms
- No Korean in UI unless implementing an explicit i18n locale later

## When adding copy

1. English only in components or shared string constants
2. Check against audience: clear to a **Korea visitor in their 20s** in &lt;1 second
3. Future i18n: keys under `lib/i18n/` or similar — default locale `en`, same voice rules
